❯ In that same style we know need to bring in the GPU architecture. The GPU uses thread concurrency to hide memory latency, but each thread has a lot of
registers, so the register file for a GPU Compute Unit, which itself is a SIMD engine, needs a sophisticated, concurrent, banked SRAM architecture to give
the executing thread access to it registers. As the SIMD engine is wide, and there will be bank conflicts that make access to the data in the SRAM have
variable latency, there tends to be a special register, called a collector, that brings all the operands together before issuing it into the SIMD engine. In
 an NVIDIA GPU, the register file has 64K logical registers that are physically managed by the concurrent banked SRAM. All this machinery is active almost
continuously to feed the SIMD engine, so yes, we have reduced the front-end overhead, but we have introduced a lot of data movement energy to support the
concurrency of many hundreds of threads to hide memory latency. If we focus on just the SIMD execution engine, the energy consumed for every ALU cycle
includes all the 64K registers and the collector registes that are buffering away the variable latency to the SRAM due to bank conflicts. We need a diagram
of this infrastructure and again an energy equation to try to simplify this to a simple analytical equation. Please generate a set of slides that support
this narrative.

