❯ It is now clear, the energy equestions are brilliant, but the state space they cover is too large, and the empirical data we have captured is too
specific. What we need to do is isolate similar functions across the architectures, CPU, GPU, TPU, KPU, and compare and contrast their energy and latency
attributes. The TPU and KPU have compute fabrics that are indivisible, for the TPU we have a 128x128 systolic array that uses a weight stationary schedule.
The KPU has a 16x16 or 32x32 programmable domain flow tile that can execute any schedule, input, weight, and output stationary, and because the KPU is
broader than just deep learning, we refer to that as, A, B, or C stationary, referencing the input and output tensors that partake in the computation. Both
TPU and KPU need a small buffer structure, typically referred to as an L1, to organize the input and output data into the array or tile. The GPUs have
Streaming Multiprocessors (NVIDIA) or Compute Units (AMD, Intel). These are the SIMT building blocks. Typically, a collection of SMs/CUs will share a
on-chip memory structure to efficiently reuse data, and to communicate data between SMs/CUs. The CPUs have ALUs and SIMD ALUs, fast L1 instruction and data
caches, and in a multi-core, an exclusive L2, and an inclusive L3. After all these structures, we will see NoC or cross-bars to connect all these compute
engines or caches to a bank of memory controllers and external memory. We thus see three distinct modeling domains: 1- the core compute engine, 2- the
on-chip memory resources, and 3- the memory controller, I/Os, and external memory. Only the first, the core compute engine is NOT workload dependendent. The
 energy demands of the on-chip and off-chip memory resources are very workload dependent, but we can simplify that by taking a characteristic data movement
pattern, such as moving a vector, a matrix, or a tensor of a particular size. For the moment, let's focus on just the core compute. We need the capture the
granularity of the different architectures, so for the CPU we have scalar ALUs and SIMD ALUs and their respective register files as the core engine. For
GPUs we have the SM/CU with the SIMD and TensorCore ALUs, their respective register files and of course all the SIMT infrastructure. This is a very coarse
block, but incredibly important to understand as all GPUs are simply compositions of these. The TPU is a input buffer and a systolic array. The KPU is
similarly, an input buffer and a PE array. Let's create a new slide deck that again highlights the energy equations to communicate how energy accumulates,
and each core compute engine for the CPU, GPU, TPU, and KPU, and highlight their granularity and energy per operation.

